Practical No. 9
Aim: Time Series Analysis
Description:
Time series analysis in BI focuses on analyzing data points collected over time to identify trends,
patterns, and seasonality, helping organizations forecast future performance and make data-driven
decisions. This analysis supports better planning, budgeting, and strategic decision-making by
turning time-based data into actionable insights.
Code:
# Sales data
sales <- c(120, 130, 150, 170, 160, 180, 200, 220, 210, 230, 250, 240,
125, 135, 145, 155, 165, 185, 205, 225, 215, 235, 255)
# Convert to time series (monthly data, 2 years)
ts_data <- ts(sales, start = c(2023, 1), frequency = 12)
# View data
print(ts_data)
# Plot time series
plot(ts_data, main = "Monthly Sales", col = "blue",
ylab = "Sales", xlab = "Time")
# Decomposition
decomp <- decompose(ts_data, type = "additive")
plot(decomp)
# Moving average
ma <- filter(ts_data, rep(1/3, 3), sides = 2)
plot(ts_data, col = "blue")
lines(ma, col = "red")
# Stationarity test
install.packages("tseries")
library(tseries)
adf.test(ts_data)
# Forecasting
install.packages("forecast")
library(forecast)
auto.arima(ts_data)
model <- auto.arima(ts_data)
summary(model)
future <- forecast(model, n = 6)
plot(future)
accuracy(future)
Conclusion:
In conclusion, time series analysis plays a vital role in business intelligence by transforming
historical time-based data into meaningful insights. It helps organizations understand past behavior,
anticipate future trends, and respond proactively to changes.
